Natural song from one of several unseen birds in dense understory of subtropical/upper tropical forest upslope from road (a P. guy was seen well feeding on flowers beside road here). The song is rather unlike other cuts of P. guy I've heard, and sounds more like P. koepckeae, but as far as I know, that latter species is unknown from the Afluente area, so that leaves me with P. guy, unless perhaps P. malaris gives a song like this in San Martin (and is present so high here).

rmk: This bird was recorded singing as part of a longtime "exploded" lek (present for at least 13 years) in fairly mature secondary forest adjacent to the Cabo Frio camp at the BDFFP. The vocalizing bird was seen perched ~3 m up in a sapling, repeatedly wagging its tail up-and-down as it called, which does not seem to be timed with the bird's near constant chipping. Aside from normalizing, the recording was unaltered. This recording is also archived at the Macaulay Library (ML241262251).

loc: Cabo Frio camp -- Biological Dynamics of Forest Fragments Project, Brazil
rmk: This bird was recorded singing as part of a longtime "exploded" lek (present for at least 13 years) in fairly mature secondary forest adjacent to the Cabo Frio camp at the BDFFP. The vocalizing bird was seen perched ~3.5 m up in some exposed twigs of a dead or dying sapling. The focus of this cut was to capture "squeal" flight calls (0:03) that the birds make at the lek; this was after the focal bird took off in pursuit of two birds that flew past it. Aside from normalizing, the recording was unaltered. This recording is also archived at the Macaulay Library (ML241263531).
